The numbers don’t lie…⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Calorie counting is a very effective way to lose weight, and while it’s not the ONLY way, it does provide a ton of insight and teaches valuable lessons.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
There are some people who say tracking calories and macros is obsessive or disordered, but it’s not, unless you make it that way.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Tracking, even if only for a few months, has a ton of benefits:⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Helps hold you accountable to ensure you’re eating the right number of calories for your goals⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Increases awareness of food quality and teaches you how your diet impacts your health.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
You’ll learn what a real serving size looks like, and if you’ve never used a food scale to track, prepare to have your mind blown 🤯 ⁣
⁣⁣
You’ll become educated about food and gain confidence knowing you can control your results.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Dietary freedom! You can go out to eat without feeling guilty and you can actually order something other than ice chips and broccoli.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
—⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Are there other ways to lose fat and save money without budgeting?  Of course, but it’s a skill that takes time to learn, just like anything else.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
Tracking allows you to get from where you are to where you’re going much faster and more efficiently.⁣⁣
⁣⁣
There are plenty of people who manage their nutrition and finances by setting boundaries, personal rules, and routines, but tracking might just be the keystone habit that helps you get the results you’ve been looking for.
What are some of your tips and tricks that have helped you stay on track with your fat loss goals while dining out? Let us know 👇🏻

If you value your mental and physical health, fitness, and your well-being, and if you want to live a long youthful life…find something you enjoy and get moving!⁣

* Eat an appropriate amount of calories for your goal
* Eat plenty of protein (1g/lb/day)
* Strength train hard 3-5x per week
* Move more - aim for 8-10k steps per day
* Get 7-9 hours of quality sleep each night
* Reduce stress levels
* Doing all of the above with consistency

I do love me some Oreos…

Look, I’m not anti-cardio. In fact I think cardio is important regardless of your goals and it can absolutely be a useful tool for fat loss, however that shouldn’t be the main focus. 

Cardio should be used to improve overall health and fitness, but it is NOT the most efficient way to achieve fat loss. 

The primary factor that determines fat loss is energy balance (the balance between the number of calories you consume and the number of calories you burn) and while cardio can help you burn calories, you’re not going to outrun those cookies. 

Additionally, the body tends to adapt to cardio over time, so at some point, you’ll likely need to progressively increase the intensity or duration of your cardio workouts, which can be difficult for most people.

Diet, on the other hand, plays a much larger role in fat loss because it has a direct impact on your energy balance. By consuming fewer calories and making healthier food choices, you can create a calorie deficit and promote fat loss, while preserving energy and time. 

Once again cardio can and should be part of a healthy lifestyle but it’s certainly not the most efficient way to lose body fat.

Diet Hack: Eat The Same Thing Every Day…

Flexible dieting is great and it removes a lot of restriction that was once associated with dieting. It allows us to eat such a wide variety of food (as long as we stay within our calories) and still lose fat.

This is a good thing...for some people.

Variety and flexibility are great as a tool when dieting, but too many options without proper planning can lead to decision fatigue, which often results in poor choices.

This is why choice minimalism can lead to much greater success.

While variety CAN be a good thing, it can also knock you off track. There were studies done that showed how food consumption increases when there is more variety in a meal or diet, and that greater dietary variety is associated with increased body weight and fat.

Does this mean that if you eat something different every day or week that you'll get fat? 

Nope, I didn't say that.

I do however believe having a dependable "boring" routine, removes the stress and worry about how and when to make adjustments.

I can confidently say that if I'm not traveling or on vacation (which is very rare) I've eaten the same few things for most of my meals...for years.

I'm not saying you have to do that, but if you can simplify your diet and standardize a few meals/snacks, it will make the process so much easier, especially if your typical week doesn't vary much.

When you remove choices it removes temptations.

Do you have to do this forever? No.
Do you have to do this for every meal? No.

But, I guarantee that if you start doing this and stick with it for a while, you will see results.

Stop the fancy shit…⁣

Am I saying you should never change your routine or experiment with different exercises?⁣

Of course not, some change and variety is good, but following exercises made up by Instagram gurus is a great way to never make solid progress. ⁣

There’s a reason the basics done consistently work and have worked for years. ⁣

NO.⁣
⁣

⁣
Here are some very simple changes you can make:⁣
Switch from barbell to dumbbell Switch from dumbbell to a machine Change the order of exercises⁣
Change your grip ⁣
Try unilateral instead of bilateral⁣
Go from sitting to standing⁣
Change your rest time Change your rep ranges⁣
Change your tempo⁣
⁣
All of these changes can be done using the exact same program you’re currently running, instead of making unnecessary changes that can slow down your progress. ⁣
⁣
And for the love of god, stop twisting sideways on the leg press to work your outer northwest glute 🤦🏻‍♂️

No, it’s not Metabolic Damage.⁣

✘ Eat sufficient protein: 0.8-1g/lb is a solid target.⁣

 ✘ Manage your stress.⁣

✘ Do your best to get plenty quality sleep. ⁣

✘ Limit cardio. Performing cardio at high frequencies, volumes, and intensities will likely have a negative impact on your weight loss efforts.⁣

Again, cardio is great and should be used to improve overall health and fitness, but it is NOT the most efficient way to achieve fat loss. 

The primary factor that determines fat loss is energy balance (the balance between the number of calories you consume and the number of calories you burn) and while cardio can help you burn calories, you’re not going to outrun those cookies. 

Diet, on the other hand, plays a much larger role in fat loss because it has a direct impact on your energy balance. By consuming fewer calories and making healthier food choices, you can create a calorie deficit and promote fat loss, while preserving energy and time.

“When I was your age, weight used to just fall off”

It's a common misconception that age is the primary factor behind weight gain/difficulty in weight management, however, age doesn't break the laws of thermodynamics.

If you consume more calories than your body expends, you'll gain weight, and if you consume fewer calories, you'll lose weight.

Age, in and of itself, does not alter these basic laws.

While there are physiological changes that occur with age, a significant factor contributing to this is a decrease in physical activity.

What’s actually going on and why does it seem harder to lose weight as we age?

Slower metabolism:  It is true that our metabolic rate slows as we get older (our bodies burn fewer calories at rest compared to younger years)  but the decline is gradual and modest.  After 60 yrs old, BMR begins to decline by only about 0.7% per year.

Muscle Mass Loss: As we age, we tend to lose muscle mass.  Muscle burns more calories at rest than fat, so a reduction in muscle can further lower our resting metabolic rate.  This is why it is important to resistance train regardless of your age! (And make sure you’re eating enough protein)

Sedentary Lifestyle: Many people become more sedentary as they age.  Desk jobs, family responsibilities, reduced mobility, lack of motivation, stress, injuries, health conditions, & more.  Less physical activity = reduced calorie expenditure.

Hormonal Shifts: Hormonal changes can influence body composition & fat distribution, particularly in women during menopause, however, they are not the sole cause of weight gain & can be managed through lifestyle choices.

While these changes may make weight management more challenging as we get older, you can’t ignore your daily habits & choices.

Regardless of your age, your dietary decisions & physical activity levels have a profound impact on your weight. If you're struggling with weight, don’t be so quick to point the finger.  Examine your lifestyle habits, eating patterns, & exercise routines.

Age is just a number, and your habits have the power to shape your health and well-being.

Look, I’m not anti-cardio. In fact I think cardio is important regardless of your goals and it can absolutely be a useful tool for fat loss, however that shouldn’t be the main focus and there are a things to consider. 

Energy compensation.  You might “think” you burned 400, 500, or 600 calories, however there is often a reduction in non-exercise energy usage in order to compensate for the energy burned during exercise/cardio. 

Additionally, the body tends to adapt to cardio over time, so at some point, you’ll likely need to progressively increase the intensity or duration of your cardio workouts, which can be difficult for most people.

Lastly, your appetite may actually INCREASE after activity which could potentially lead to you eating more. 

Again, cardio is great and should be used to improve overall health and fitness, but it is NOT the most efficient way to achieve fat loss. 

The primary factor that determines fat loss is energy balance (the balance between the number of calories you consume and the number of calories you burn) and while cardio can help you burn calories, you’re not going to outrun those cookies. 

Diet, on the other hand, plays a much larger role in fat loss because it has a direct impact on your energy balance. By consuming fewer calories and making healthier food choices, you can create a calorie deficit and promote fat loss, while preserving energy and time. 

TLDR: cardio should be part of a healthy lifestyle but it’s certainly not the most efficient way to lose body fat.
